@article{Kassis1986,
abstract = {Engrailed (en) is a gene involved in proper segmentation of the Drosophila embryo. The predicted en protein contains a homeodomain and regions rich in polyalanine, polyglutamine, polyglutamate/aspartate and serine. We have taken an evolu-tionary approach to define which regions may be of fun-damental importance by examining the D. virUis genomic sequence homologous to the D. melanogaster en primary transcription unit. Sequence homology begins at the first ATG of a long open reading frame yielding proteins of 584 and 552 amino acids for the D. virilis and D. melanogaster pro-teins, respectively. The predicted amino acid sequence can be divided into conserved and non-conserved domains. The C-terminal 30{\%} of the protein (which includes the homeodo-main) is completely conserved. In the N-terminal 70{\%} of the protein, the overall conservation is 71{\%}, but non-conservative amino acid changes occur in clusters and there are short stret-ches of highly conserved sequence. A region rich in glutamate and aspartate is conserved and has homology to an 18-amino acid sequence present in members of the myc family of pro-teins. Major differences in the size of the two proteins occur in regions of non-conserved repeated sequences. In the in-trons of the engrailed transcription units there are long stret-ches of conservation, suggesting this DNA may be of functional importance. Key words: developmental gene/DNA sequence conservation/ Drosophilalengrailed gene/myc gene dicates functional importance (Wilson et al., 1977), the homeo-domain must play a crucial role within the proteins which contain it. Recent evidence suggests that at least one function en-coded by this domain is sequence-specific DNA binding (Laughon and Scott, 1984; McGinnis et al., 1984a; Desplan et al., 1985; and in preparation). Besides the homeodomain, the protein-coding regions of many developmental genes share another feature, regions rich in a single amino acid (Laughon et al., 1985). These are predominantly en-coded by trinucleotide repeats. The most prevalent of these is a CAX repeat (alternatively called a strep, opa or M repeat; Kidd et al., 1983; Wharton et al., 1985b; McGinnis et al., 1984a) which codes for polyglutamine (Laughon et al., 1985). Several repeat regions can occur in a single protein. For example, the predicted engrailed protein contains various regions rich in glut-amine, alanine, serine and acidic amino acids (Poole et al., 1985). The function of these regions is unclear, but their presence in so many of the developmentally important genes of Drosophila may mean that they serve some functional or structural role in the proteins which contain them. An example of such a gene is the Drosophila segmentation gene, engrailed (en). En is required for development of the posterior part of each segment and for the maintenance of seg-ment and compartment borders (Lawrence and Morata, 1976; Kornberg, 198 1a, 198 1b; Lawrence and Struhl, 1982). It is ex-pressed early in development in a striped pattern where the ex-pressing regions are the progenitors of the posterior part of each segment (Kornberg et al., 1985; Fjose et al., 1985; DiNardo et al., 1985; Weir and Kornberg, 1985; Ingham et al., 1985). ATG Introduction It is increasingly evident that sequence homologies between},
